  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Adapting social protection schemes to contexts of volatile prices/gender equity</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">A core policy response used to meet immediate food needs in food crises is the delivery of cash or vouchers through social protection schemes. However, the last global food price hike revealed that high food prices undermine the value of cash -based transfers resulting in a significant drop in beneficiaries&apos; purchasing power and increased burden on women, suggesting that food distribution might be a better option.    This research aims to learn from social protection programmes, and look for ways of ensuring their flexibility in times of price crisis, in particular looking at food reserves and ensuring that programmes support gender equity.</narrative>
  </description>
